additionalInformation: BILL SUMMARY - As introduced it clarifies when a victim has the right to have a sexual assault advocate present and establishes that sexual assault advocates are certified by the Office of Victim Services and Justice Grants. It establishes a victims right to receive information about their case from prosecutors and MPD. It establishes confidentiality and mandatory reporting requirements for sexual assault victim advocates. It clarifies victims rights when receiving medical care and among other things expands the definition of sexual contact to include the removal of a person's clothing without consent.
title: Sexual Assault Victims' Rights Amendment Act of 2019

additionalInformation: BILL SUMMARY - As introduced it prohibits the reporting of criminal history information related to records that have been sealed, expunged, or set aside, or that did not result in a conviction. It authorizes the Office of Human Rights to adjudicate complaints filed under this act and establishes penalties for noncompliance.

additionalInformation: BILL SUMMARY - As introduced it authorizes the Mayor to submit a request to the Office of the Attorney General to petition the Court to appoint a receiver and shortens time frames to expedite the process. It requires the Court to retain and monitor cases. It authorizes the Court to order any owner to contribute funds in excess of the rents received to fund the abatement, reimburse the District, relocate tenants, and to operate and maintain the building while in receivership.
title: Landlord Accountability through Expedited Receivership Amendment Act of 2019

additionalInformation: BILL SUMMARY - As introduced it prevents negligent property owners from operating multiple non-compliant properties. It provides subpoena power to the Mayor when the District uncovers a certain number of housing code violations in a single unit and in a single building. At that point, the Mayor is authorized to subpoena ownership records of all properties owned in the District by the non-compliant owner.
title: Landlord Transparency Amendment Act of 2019

additionalInformation: BILL SUMMARY - As introduced it reforms the District's record sealing process, by mandating automatic sealing for non-dangerous, non-convictions, shortening the waiting periods before a person is eligible to seal their record, and expanding the eligibility of who can seal their record.
title: Second Chance Amendment Act of 2019

additionalInformation: BILL SUMMARY - As introduced it extends the duration of a declared state of emergency from 30 to 60 calendar days and requires publication of a declaration of an emergency on the District government website.
title: Natural Disaster Consumer Protection Amendment Act of 2019

additionalInformation: BILL SUMMARY - As introduced it prohibits the registration and possession of ghost guns in the District of Columbia.  Ghost guns are firearms that, after the removal of all parts other than a receiver, cannot be detected by a metal detector.

additionalInformation: BILL SUMMARY - As introduced it amends current laws regarding sealing and expungement of criminal records by allowing for automatic sealing and expungement of certain cases. additionalInformation: BILL SUMMARY - As introduced it authorizes that upon a judicial finding of an intrafamily offense, the parties may obtain a divorce within 3 months of filing a complaint provided that they have lived separate and apart since the date of the offense. Among other things, it prohibits an award of alimony and any interest in the injured spouse's pension and retirement benefits or attorney fees when there has been a judicial finding of an intrafamily offense.

additionalInformation: BILL SUMMARY - As introduced it creates regulations that govern the removal of bedbugs. It also requires landlords to notify adjoining tenants of infestations. additionalInformation: BILL SUMMARY - As introduced it requires District of Columbia Public Schools to include in its budget submission to the Council detailed information for each school's funding, a separate line-item for at-risk funding for each school, and a narrative description of programs and services funded by at-risk funds retained by the Chancellor. It also requires that Public Charter Schools make publicly available a report that delineates all programs or services supported by funds allocated during the previous fiscal year. The Public Charter School Board may withhold funds allocated pursuant to this section from a Public Charter School that fails to timely publish the report required.

additionalInformation: BILL SUMMARY - As introduced it prohibits nondisclosure agreements or other documents, as a condition of employment or otherwise, from preventing the disclosure of factual information related to claims alleging certain sexual offenses, harassment or discrimination. It also prohibits retaliation and provides remedies involving such claims. The Attorney General and the Mayor are also required to submit an annual report to the Council regarding public funds paid for awards and settlements for claims of misconduct.

title: Sexual Misconduct Sunshine Amendment Act of 2019

additionalInformation:
LEGISLATION SUMMARY - Law 23-72 provides that an owner of housing of 4 to 10 units who reduces the number of units pay a fee to the Mayor and that fee be deposited into the Housing Production Trust Fund. It provides that by a specified date all fees above $692,000 annually collected pursuant to the Conversion of Rental Housing to Condominium or Cooperative Status Act of 1980 also be deposited in the Housing Production Trust Fund. It also provides for damages and legal action for tenants whose unit has been repossessed for personal use and occupancy and the landlord has subsequently received rent. 

FUNDING NOTE - This bill is Subject to Appropriations. See Fiscal Impact Statement in "Other Documents" tab.

additionalInformation:
LEGISLATIVE SUMMARY - Law 23-57 makes changes to the District's sexual assault response system. It addresses whether the benefits of a victim dependent on a primary insurance holders policy will be categorized as a collateral source. It establishes deadlines for the Department of Forensic Sciences to process physical evidence. It prohibits hospitals from charging victims for costs related to physical evidence recovery kits. It expands membership of the Sexual Assault Response Team (Team) and its duties. It establishes reporting requirements for the Team to the Mayor and Council. It also exempts Sexual Assault Counselors from mandatory reporting in certain cases and requires that specific specialized units of the MPD provide certain information to sexual assault victims over the age of 13.

Incorporates provisions from Bill 22-222.

BILL SUMMARY - As introduced Bill 23-72 establishes the licensing and regulation infrastructure for the production, sale, consumption, and testing of retail marijuana and retail marijuana-infused products. It establishes what actions involving marijuana shall not constitute a civil or criminal offense or be a basis for seizure or forfeiture of assets under District law. It also requires the Clerk of the Court to proactively expunge certain offenses and notify the person entitled to expungement, the prosecutor, pretrial, corrections and community supervision agencies of the expungement. It also establishes a dedicated marijuana fund, which shall consist of all sales tax and excise tax revenue from retail marijuana.

title: Department of Buildings Establishment Act of 2019

additionalInformation:
Vetoed by Mayor on January 13, 2021.  Council override of veto approved on February 2, 2021.

BILL SUMMARY - As introduced it establishes, as a subordinate agency within the executive branch of the District government, the Department of Buildings. The Department is charged with promoting the health, safety, and quality of life of residents and visitors in the District of Columbia by reviewing proposed plans for technical sufficiency, issuing permits, inspecting the built environment, regulating land use and development, and enforcing the regulations and codes governing building construction, rental housing conditions, building maintenance, and building safety. 

FUNDING NOTE - This bill is Subject to Appropriations. See Fiscal Impact Statement in "Other Documents".

additionalInformation: BILL SUMMARY - As introduced it allows holders of accounts with digital assets to give access to these accounts to fiduciaries. additionalInformation:
LEGISLATION SUMMARY - Law 23-113 requires that employers who have employees who turn down parking benefits offer a Clean air Transportation Fringe Benefit in an amount equal to or more than the market value of the parking benefit minus the employee's contribution to the parking expense subject to the maximum tax-free benefit allowed by the IRS.  If the employee declines both the parking benefit and the Clean-air Transportation Fringe Benefit the employer must increase its financial contribution to the health coverage, and/or the taxable wages, to where the employer contribution equals the market value of the benefit offered. The employer also has the option to pay a Clean Air Compliance fee of $100 per month for each employee who is offered parking benefits, cease to offer parking benefits, or develop a transportation demand management plan that the District of Columbia Department of Transportation has determined is likely to reduce the number of commuter trips employees made by car or taxi the previous year. 

Incorporates provisions from Bill 22-175.

FUNDING NOTE - This bill is Subject to Appropriations. See Fiscal Impact Statement in "Other Documents" tab.

additionalInformation: BILL SUMMARY - As introduced it requires greater transparency in charter school administration regarding contracts greater than $25,000. It requires specific information in charter school annual reports. Among other things, it requires that the Public Charter School Board deliver a report to the Council describing the number and cost of requests for information made pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act. LEGISLATIVE SUMMARY - Law 23-77 provides for an annual payment to certain providers of direct services to persons with developmental disabilities. additionalInformation: LEGISLATIVE SUMMARY - Law 23-98 specifies the required contents of a notification of a security breach to a person whose personal information is included in a breach and clarifies time frames for reporting. It specifies security requirements for protection of personal information which if not followed may be subject to an unfair or deceptive trade practice violation. Among other things, it requires the provision of 18 months of identity theft prevention services when the breach results in the release of social security or tax identification numbers.

additionalInformation: LEGISLATION SUMMARY - Law 23-50 updates the ABC Board's enforcement powers including revoking a licensees license if the Board has cause to believe that the licensee has been evicted from or has otherwise vacated the licensed premises. It removes some burdensome requirements from internet licensees that are not in furtherance of peace, order, quiet, and public safety. It clarifies that unless otherwise authorized wholesalers and manufacturers are not permitted to sell alcoholic beverages to an unlicensed person and that wholesalers are required to store products in the District of Columbia for a minimum of 4 hours at the licensed location and keep inventory records. It also, among other things, requires the Office of Tax and Revenue to notify the Board when a licensee is the subject of a citation, revocation, or other enforcement action.
title: Alcoholic Beverage Enforcement Amendment Act of 2019

additionalInformation: BILL SUMMARY - As introduced it establishes an electronic reporting system for all Local Education Agencies (LEAs) and public school budget expenditures to collect comparable data from schools and LEAs. It creates a line-item for at-risk funding for each school and delineates how DCPS and the Public Charter School Board shall delineate costs and expenditures in their budgets. It requires that public charter schools comply with the District of Columbia Administrative Procedures Act and the Office of the State Superintendent of Education is required to create an electronic reporting system for public school expenditures for the public.

additionalInformation: BILL SUMMARY - As introduced it includes establishing a permanent early warning and support system to expand the grade range covered  by the system to grades 1 through 11. The system will track how individual students are performing on certain indicators of high school and college readiness, including scoring a 2 or lower on any Partnership for Assessment of Readiness for College and Careers exam. It establishes the Office of Graduate Support to support recent graduates struggling to find employment or at college.  The Office of the State Superintendent for Education is required to track outcomes for DCPS graduates and provide recommendations to the Office of Graduate Support and Department of Employment Services.

additionalInformation: LEGISLATION SUMMARY - Law 23-116 establishes time frames for a health professional employer to report action taken against a health professional to a board, commission, or authority and creates sanctions for failure to comply. It also requires a health professional to submit to a board, commission or authority responsible for licensing, registering, or certifying the health professional within 10 business days notice of a malpractice judgment, settlement, or that the health professional has been convicted of a crime. Among other things it requires the Health Occupations Boards to ensure that a practitioner or dispenser is registered with the prescription drug monitoring program before renewing, reactivating, or reinstating a license.

additionalInformation: LEGISLATIVE SUMMARY - Law 23-54 increases the alcohol by volume percentage for wine from 15 to 21 percent and allows holders of wine pub and distillery pub permits to ship products directly to District residents. It allows District residents to manufacture beer and wine in their home without a license if it is for personal use and allows pub permit holders to manufacture alcoholic beverages off-site if the production facility is within 600 feet of the licensed premises. Among other things, it amends pub permits to pub endorsements, and establishes wine pub endorsement, brew pub endorsement and distillery pub endorsement fees.

BILL SUMMARY - As introduced it creates a regulatory scheme for the cultivation, manufacture, distribution, and sale of marijuana and marijuana produces sold for non-medical use in the District.  It renames the Alcoholic Beverage Regulation Administration to the Alcoholic Beverage and Cannabis Administrations (ABCA) and gives it the authority to regulate and license the sale, use, distribution, and cultivation of marijuana in the District.

additionalInformation:
LEGISLATION SUMMARY - Law 23-158 requires the Mayor to install sidewalks on both sides of a street, to connect new sidewalks to existing sidewalks and to mark unmarked crosswalks. It provides that the Department of Transportation (DDOT) not issue public space permits for certain projects unless the plans include installing new sidewalks, bicycle lanes or cycle tracks, or marked crosswalks and the applicant has met the requirements of previous permits and returned crosswalks and bicycle lanes to their pre-construction condition.  It also requires that DDOT make certain information publicly available and easily searchable, and issue reports on how projects or recommendations increase transportation safety and provide equitable access to safety goals. It requires Council approval of the Multimodal Long-Range Transportation Plan. It prohibits drivers from using headphones or earbuds that cover both ears while operating a motor vehicle and expands when points may be assessed for distracted driving violations. Among other things, it reduces the maximum driving speed on certain roads to 20 mph and prohibits turning on red in certain intersections. It also requires 10 days' notice regarding statements about regulating vehicular or pedestrian traffic, if the proposed installation, modification, or removal of the statement will increase safety at a location identified as a high-risk intersection in the Multimodal Long-Range Transportation Plan. 

FUNDING NOTE - This bill is Subject to Appropriations. See Fiscal Impact Statement.

LEGISLATION SUMMARY - Law 23-158 requires the Mayor to install sidewalks on both sides of a street, to connect new sidewalks to existing sidewalks and to mark unmarked crosswalks. It provides that the Department of Transportation (DDOT) not issue public space permits for certain projects unless the plans include installing new sidewalks, bicycle lanes or cycle tracks, or marked crosswalks and the applicant has met the requirements of previous permits and returned crosswalks and bicycle lanes to their pre-construction condition.  It also requires that DDOT make certain information publicly available and easily searchable, and issue reports on how projects or recommendations increase transportation safety and provide equitable access to safety goals. It requires Council approval of the Multimodal Long-Range Transportation Plan. It prohibits drivers from using headphones or earbuds that cover both ears while operating a motor vehicle and expands when points may be assessed for distracted driving violations. Among other things, it reduces the maximum driving speed on certain roads to 20 mph and prohibits turning on red in certain intersections. It also requires 10 days' notice regarding statements about regulating vehicular or pedestrian traffic, if the proposed installation, modification, or removal of the statement will increase safety at a location identified as a high-risk intersection in the Multimodal Long-Range Transportation Plan. 

FUNDING NOTE - This bill is Subject to Appropriations. See Fiscal Impact Statement.

additionalInformation: BILL SUMMARY - As introduced it requires the Office of Police Complaints to review data and make recommendations to the District of Columbia Housing Authority and the Department of Consumer and Regulatory Affairs, and special police officers related to police misconduct, complaints, discipline, use of force and in custody deaths. title: Dementia Training for Direct Care Workers Act of 2019

additionalInformation:
BILL SUMMARY - As introduced it requires dementia training for direct care workers, which includes staff whose work involves extensive contact with residents or program participants of residential facilities or home-and community-based programs that provide supportive services. 

FUNDING NOTE - This bill is Subject to Appropriations. See Fiscal Impact Statement in "Other Documents".

additionalInformation:
BILL SUMMARY - As introduced it requires the Department of Transportation to create rules governing electric mobility devices. It requires a permit to operate an electric mobility device fleet. It establishes fleet maintenance requirements. It requires a 24 hour hotline to report complaints regarding fleets. It bans the use of electric scooters between 10pm and 4am. additionalInformation:
LEGISLATION SUMMARY - Law 23-80 clarifies the soil testing requirements for the urban farm tax abatement and allows the District to enter into a lease agreement with a qualified applicant to create and maintain an urban farm on vacant land. It also allows the Department of Energy and the Environment to waive soil testing requirements for a lessee who does not plant in or use the site soil, but instead uses, for example, raised beds, greenhouses, or hydroponic towers and ensures that the produce does not come into contact with the site soil. 

FUNDING NOTE - This bill is Subject to Appropriations. See Fiscal Impact Statement in "Other Documents".

additionalInformation: BILL SUMMARY - As introduced it establishes when DCRA shall require construction contractors shall provide proof of financial responsibility and an estimated cost of construction. It requires reporting of lapsed insurance for contractors by the insurer. It requires housing providers to provide documentation of a Basic Business License at the time of filing an action for possession or when attempting to raise the rent. It establishes an expiration date for permits issued for work. It establishes rat abatement protocols for applicants of a demolition permit. It also requires those doing a construction or condo conversion to post a bond or letter of credit with the Mayor in the amount of 10% of the estimated cost. It establishes additional certification requirements for housing code inspectors. It establishes the District of Columbia Construction Commission appointed by the Mayor to set the standards for licensing contractors in the District among other things.

additionalInformation: BILL SUMMARY - As introduced It requires automatic sealing of non-convictions, eligible misdemeanors, and eligible felonies after a certain period of time. It shifts the burden of proof for record sealing from the individual to the prosecution. It also clarifies that failure to pay fines and fees does not count towards completion of a sentence. It also includes certain non-violent offences as "eligible felonies".

additionalInformation: BILL SUMMARY - As introduced Bill 23-405 increases the mandatory minimum motor vehicle insurance requirements for property damage liability and third-party liability coverage. It also increases the mandatory minimum motor vehicle insurance requirements for property damage liability, third-party liability, underinsured motor vehicle, and enhanced underinsured motor vehicle coverage. It also requires insurers to provide enhanced underinsured motor vehicle coverage under a passenger vehicle liability insurance policy among other things
title: Motor Vehicle Insurance Modernization Amendment Act of 2019

title: Department of Forensic Sciences Services and Fees Clarification Amendment Act of 2019

additionalInformation: BILL SUMMARY - As introduced Bill 23-411 requires the Chief Medical Examiner to investigate all maternal mortalities that occur in the District of Columbia. It also allows the Chief Medical Examiner to investigate severe maternal morbidity following an unexpected outcome of labor and delivery that results in significant short-term or long-term consequences to a woman's health that include at least one of the morbidity indicators specified by the U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.
title: Investigating Maternal Mortalities Amendment Act of 2019

title: Ignition Interlock Program Amendment Act of 2019

additionalInformation: BILL SUMMARY - As introduced Bill 23-415 repeals the provision that exempts a violation of the Distracted Driving Safety Act of 2004 from the assessment of points unless the violation contributes to an accident.
title: Vision Zero Distracted Driving Amendment Act of 2019

additionalInformation: LEGISLATION SUMMARY - Law 23-188 adds provisions to the Comprehensive Newborn Screening Program to establish discharge standards and authorizes penalties for failure to comply with the standards or perform the necessary screens. It would also authorize the Department of Health to collect information from hospitals and birthing facilities to create a report card regarding compliance with newborn screening requirements, lactation support services, parent education, discharge standards, and clinical quality measures.  It also creates a Perinatal and Infant Health Advisory Committee that would advise on ways to reduce preterm birth and newborn screening activities.

additionalInformation: BILL SUMMARY - As introduced Bill 23-429 prohibits balance billing, which is a bill sent to an enrollee by an out-of-network provider or facility for health care services provided to the enrollee after the provider billed amount is not reimbursed by the health insurer. It creates procedures for the resolution and payment of balance bills including an arbitration process. The Department of Insurance, Securities, and Banking must enforce the provisions of the act, create a report on the use of arbitration, and create a consumer rights notice.

BILL SUMMARY - As introduced Bill 23-432 provides funding for the Legacy Business Program via a portion of the DC Supply Schedule. It establishes the legacy business assistance program to provide a commercial lease renewal process and financial assistance to landlords and eligible legacy business. A legacy business is one that has been continuously eligible for certification as a local business enterprise for 15 consecutive years or as a small business enterprise for 10 consecutive years and contributed to the history or identity of the District or its neighborhoods. 

FUNDING NOTE - This bill is Subject to Appropriations. Please see Fiscal Impact Statement below.

additionalInformation:

The Chairman is referring this legislation sequentially to the Committee on Judiciary and Public Safety and the Committee of the Whole (section 3) and then to the Committee of the Whole with comments from the Committee on Facilities and Procurement.

BILL SUMMARY - As introduced Bill 23-440 establishes a uniform standard for occupational licensing boards to consider only pending criminal accusations or prior convictions directly related to the occupation for which the license is sought. Adverse decisions must be subject to mitigating evidence submitted by the applicant. The Mayor and the Deputy Mayor for Public Safety and Justice are required to submit reports to the Council involving adverse decisions and their collateral consequences.

additionalInformation: BILL SUMMARY - As introduced Bill 23-441 requires Local Education Agencies to submit to the Office of the State Superintendent of Education plans to administer an annual academic assessment for all students from kindergarten to third grade to monitor progress in reading and comprehension. additionalInformation: BILL SUMMARY - As introduced Bill 23-442 extends labor and employment protections to domestic workers who perform work in and about private households in D.C.  Domestic workers include an individual paid by hiring entities and provides domestic services to an individual or household in or about the private home, who is compensated  for the performance of domestic services. It also provides community-based education, outreach, and enforcement of domestic workers' labor and employment rights.

additionalInformation: BILL SUMMARY - As introduced Bill 23-456 authorizes the Office of the Attorney General to issue subpoenas for documents and testimony as part of a receivership investigation and clarifies the basis for the appointment of a Housing Receiver. It authorizes the Court to order anyone in the care and control of the property to contribute funds in excess of the rents to abate violations. It provides for the relocation of displaced tenants and the upkeep and debts of the building while in receivership. It establishes when a receivership can be terminated and clarifies when the court can enjoin the respondents.

additionalInformation: BILL SUMMARY - As introduced this bill establishes that expenditures on school-administered theatrical and music performances shall be an allowable expenditure from a school's Student Activity Fund. Theatrical and music performances include the planning, rehearsal, or presentation of a musical, staged play, choral production, orchestral or band concert, variety show, improvised or sketch comedy performance, or other live performance.

additionalInformation: BILL SUMMARY - As introduced Bill 23-490 requires the Chief Financial Officer to approve or deny an application for pre-approval of certain homestead deduction, senior and disabled tax relief deductions, or exemptions for qualifying lower income homeownership households, within two weeks after receiving the application. It provides for clarified audit and collection procedures among other things.

title: Healthy Hospitals Amendment Act of 2019

additionalInformation:
BILL SUMMARY - As introduced Bill 23-506 requires a plan for comprehensive organics site management and recycling infrastructure. Among other things it requires a uniform recycling labeling scheme, requires waste collectors to address contamination in recyclables and compostables and requires the Mayor to impose a surcharge on recycling disposed of at District transfer stations when they exceed a contamination threshold. It establishes additional standards regarding the use of compostable disposable food service ware such as requiring the use of reusable food service ware when providing food for consumption. It also establishes a reuse and donation program to reduce waste in landfills and incinerators. 

FUNDING NOTE - This bill is Subject to Appropriations.  Please see the Fiscal Impact Statement under Other Documents.

BILL SUMMARY - As introduced Bill 23-506 requires a plan for comprehensive organics site management and recycling infrastructure. Among other things it requires a uniform recycling labeling scheme, requires waste collectors to address contamination in recyclables and compostables and requires the Mayor to impose a surcharge on recycling disposed of at District transfer stations when they exceed a contamination threshold. It establishes additional standards regarding the use of compostable disposable food service ware such as requiring the use of reusable food service ware when providing food for consumption. It also establishes a reuse and donation program to reduce waste in landfills and incinerators. 

FUNDING NOTE - This bill is Subject to Appropriations.  Please see the Fiscal Impact Statement under Other Documents.

additionalInformation: BILL SUMMARY - As introduced Bill 23-515 requires the Office of the State Superintendent of Education (OSSE) to publicly report data relevant to understanding teacher retention and attrition and provide an annual report of their findings. Findings shall include school, local education agency, and state level data on why teachers decide to leave the teaching profession as well as report on the use of long-term substitute teachers in schools. It shall also report on unfilled vacancies that remain at the beginning of a school year.

additionalInformation: BILL SUMMARY - As introduced Bill 23-545 provides remediation for subcontractors in the event of non-payment by contractors or higher-tier subcontractors. It requires that payments be made to subcontractors within 7 days of receipt of funds paid to contractor from the District agency.  It also standardizes program compliance verification with a site visit, creates an anonymous violation reporting mechanism, and incentivizes small business subcontracting. Among other things it also closes loopholes to prevent program abuse.

It authorizes a state to allow a licensee from another member state to practice as a physical therapist or work as a physical therapist assistant in the remote state under its laws and rules. The practice of physical therapy occurs in the members state where the patient is located at the time of the encounter.

additionalInformation: BILL SUMMARY - As introduced Bill 23-570  requires the Department of Employment Services ("DOES") to permit organizations to provide DOES with qualified candidates for inclusion in the First Source Register. The register was established to ensure that District residents are given priority for new jobs created by municipal financing and development programs. It requires DOES to proactively identify individuals who are "hard to serve" and to develop standard operating procedures for its role in First Source.  Among other things, it requires that the workforce intermediary program be used exclusively for First Source projects or contracts.

additionalInformation:
BILL SUMMARY - As introduced Bill 23-640 requires the Water and Sewer Authority to allow a public comment period regarding any establishment or adjustment of retail water and sewer rates beginning on the date of publication of the notice of a public hearing. It requires a copy of Cost of Service studies be transmitted to the Mayor and Council and posted on the Authority's website. The Authority is also required to provide notice to residential customers of the requirement to dispute a contested bill in writing within 30 days.  The Authority must also prescribe annual reporting requirements regarding the lead water service line replacement assistance program. additionalInformation: BILL SUMMARY - As introduced Bill 23-644 prohibits internet service providers that provide broadband internet access service from engaging in specified actions concerning the treatment of lawful Internet traffic such as blocking lawful content, applications, services, or non-harmful devices. "Adverse Childhood Experiences" are traumatic experiences that occur during childhood, including physical, emotional or sexual abuse, physical and emotional neglect, exposure to violence and household dysfunction, among other things.

additionalInformation: BILL SUMMARY - As introduced Bill 23-873 clarifies certain definitions in the Rental Housing Act of 1985 regarding hardship petitions. It sets additional guidelines and requirements for proposed capital improvements to rental property.  It caps hardship rent surcharges at 5% per year and eliminates any rent adjustment based on a voluntary agreement. Among other things, it requires proposed substantial rehabilitations must be depreciable and the cost recoverable pursuant to Internal Revenue Service standards.
title: Rent Stabilization Program Reform and Expansion Amendment Act of 2020

additionalInformation: BILL SUMMARY - As introduced Bill 23-919 includes both probate and non-probate assets in the elected spousal share of a surviving spouse or domestic partner.  It allows real property held by spouses or domestic partners by tenancy of the entirety to convey to a trustee to retain immunity from creditiors while in the trust. It also allows a surviving spouse or domestic partner to claim a deceased spousal unused exclusion amount on the estate tax.

BILL SUMMARY - As introduced Bill 23-923 requires the Office on Returning Citizen Affairs to assess the needs of children in the District of Columbia whose parents are incarcerated.  A comprehensive needs assessment and a strategic plan outlining how the District will specifically meet the social, emotional, economic, educational, housing, health, mental health, and other needs of children whose parents are incarcerated shall be submitted to the Mayor and the Council.

additionalInformation: BILL SUMMARY - As introduced Bill 23-972 authorizes the Rental Housing Commission to determine the annual guaranteed profit margin applicable to rent surcharges authorized by a hardship petition.  It caps annual hardship petition increases to 5% and requires the Rent Administrator to review a hardship petition and to issue the housing provider and affected tenants an audit report and recommendations for the final disposition of the hardship petition within 60 days of submission. It establishes the rebuttable presumption that a housing provider has filed a petition in bad faith under certain circumstances. It establishes penalties and fines for housing providers that attempt to collect or collect a hardship rent surcharge without the prior approval of a petition or after it has expired.
